<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900719-0057</DOCNO><DOCID>900719-0057.</DOCID><HL>   United Auto Workers,   GM Open Contract Talks</HL><DATE>07/19/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C9</SO><CO>   LABOR GM</CO><IN>AUTOMOBILES (AUT)</IN><LP>   DETROIT -- United Auto Workers President Owen Bieberopened contract talks with General Motors Corp. by vowing to&quot;change the way GM does business&quot; so that no more unionmembers lose their jobs.   But Alfred S. Warren, GM's vice president and top labornegotiator, replied that the company wants the union toaccept measures that will cut costs in the auto maker'sparts-making operations. GM also wants the union's help innarrowing the approximately $560-per-car gap between GM'shealth-care costs and those of U.S. assembly factoriesoperated by Japanese auto makers.</LP><TEXT>   Both Mr. Bieber and Mr. Warren said they want to resolvetheir differences and produce a new, three-year contractbefore the current pact ends Sept. 14.   Union bargainers will push for job guarantees that willforce GM to lay off salaried workers before UAW members, Mr.Bieber said.   Although Mr. Warren declined to be specific about GM'sproposals for cutting labor costs in its parts businesses,the vice president said, &quot;If the union offered me a lowerwage scale (for parts workers) I'd take it.&quot; GM parts workersnow earn the same average $15.74 hourly wage as assemblyworkers -- well above the average pay at competitive, non-GMparts operations.   As for health benefits, Mr. Warren said current UAW plansadd about $622 to the cost of each vehicle GM builds, whichcompares to about $60 for U.S-built Japanese vehicles.</TEXT></DOC>